projects: [{'title': 'The Class Conference Lisbon, 2017', 'date': {'start': {'month': 11, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}, 'end': {'month': 11, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}}, 'description': 'With 600+ attendees, this is the perfect opportunity to expand your network and meet experts in student housing, talent attraction, and residence life- all while taking part in an extensive programme of panel discussions, interactive sessions, and city tours. Our goal is to build ecosystems where cities, universities, and the real estate community cooperate to make student living efficient, international, and welcoming. This year’s theme is “Building Bridges Over Growing Barriers”, and we will focus on how collaborations between cities, universities, and providers/developers can increase and embrace internationalization in times of political uncertainty.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Andreas', 'last_name': 'Chrysanthou', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Data Analyst at PharmAccess Foundation'}]}, {'title': 'MA Thesis - Measuring the effects of green urban space on property values using GIS metrics: A case study for the city of Rotterdam', 'date': {'start': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}, 'end': {'month': 8, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}}, 'description': 'This research focuses on the effects of green space on property values in the city of Rotterdam. The concept of environmental injustice is examined; in which the government promotes the development of green areas mainly in high-income neighborhoods. An OLS regression analysis using 2,654 properties in Rotterdam, reveals a negative effect on property values for green space located within 100 meters from each transaction. However, after controlling for historical land usage in a TSLS regression analysis, it is revealed that green coverage within 300 meters from each transaction has a significant positive effect on property values. Furthermore, it is estimated that the effect of green coverage depends mainly on the property’s distance to the Central Business District.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Andreas', 'last_name': 'Chrysanthou', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Data Analyst at PharmAccess Foundation'}]}, {'title': 'BA Thesis - The effect of environmental amenities on house prices: The inner city of London', 'date': {'start': {'month': 7, 'day': None, 'year': 2016}, 'end': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2016}}, 'description': 'Urban residents distribute a rapidly increasing implicit value on the presence of environmental amenities in close proximity to their properties. This study estimates the effect of distance to the nearest green area and water source on property values in the inner city of London. The statistical analysis reveals significant negative effects of increasing distance between properties and green/water areas, both on individual and on aggregate levels.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Andreas', 'last_name': 'Chrysanthou', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Data Analyst at PharmAccess Foundation'}]}]
